{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_chestnut_ver01/data/sn91068748/00415667401/1920122401/0474.xml":{"full_text":"PUBLISHED EVERY FRIDAY BY\nThe Herald Publishing o., Inc.\nJ, T. Stawback\nF, M. Shuts\nEditor\nManager\nSiWripOo $2.00 a Tear in Advance\nTELEPHQNE 570\nEntered as Second Clau Matter April\n8, i914, at the Post Oflice at Roanoke\nRapids, Ndrtb Carolina, under Act of\nMarch 8, 1879.\nAll communication, ehonld be\naddressed to the Herald Publishing Co.\nPersons wishing return of msa, muiit in\nall rases enclose stamps.\nAll cards of thanks, resolutions of re\nspect,' etc., etc.. will be charged for at\nthe rate of ten cents per line, cash\nmust accompany article in all cases ex\ncept here customer has a regular ac\ncount. No insertions made for lex\nthan 26 cents.\nFriday, December 24, 1920\nChristmas frills make January\nbills.\nDon't forget to use Red Cross\nChristmas Seals.\nDown\nschools!\nwith taxes!\nPoorer roads!\nFewer\nCoL S. Claus is expected to ar\nrive in the city some time after\nmidnight\nHere is the day when a whole\nlot of us will do our Christmas\nshopping late.\nCol. Bryan in Full Accord with\nSenator Harding headline. De\nmocracy, here is thy sting!\nYou'll have to hand it to Con\nstantine-he's the only kinglet\nwho has \"come back\" so far.\nShoes are predicted to retai\naround five dollars next Spring\nwhich sounds more like the war\nis over than anything we've\nheard yet\nWhy not eliminate taxes alto\ngether? At their lowest they\nare annoying, if not expensive.\nSurely Halifax can be as modern\nas Dahomy. where the tax col\nlector is not abroad in the land\nand would probably be broiled\nlor supper by his irritated con\nstituents shortly after his ap'\npointment\nThree and one half million\nchildren in Central and Eastern\nEurope are hoping, not for\nSanta Claus, but for food to stay\nthe pangs of hunger. Experts\nof the American Relief Commis\nsion estimate that if America\nfails them more than a million\nof these children will succumb\nthis winter to the ghastly spectre\nof want If you have not already\nhelped, you are urged to do so\ntoday to the full extent of your\nability. Ten dollars will save\nthe life of a child until spring\nand the harvest time. Can you\nnot save the life of one of these\nlittle ones?\nDonations may be made to\nthis office or direct to Mr. Henry\nA. Page, Chairman, Aberdeen,\nN. C, and such is the condition\nto-day over there that he gives\ntwice who gives quickly.\nCLEAR MANDATE TO\nGO FORWARD\nThe news coming out of Ral\neigh indicates that a resolute en\ndeavor is to be made to keep\nNorth Carolina in the same old\nrut The estimates for the state\ninstitutions, we are informed,\nare to be cut ruthlessly. Just how\ngreat the damage will -'.be we\nhave is yet no means of knowing;\nbut it is plain enough that noth\ninsr like the $18,000,000 needed\nwill be granted\nWell, if the solons had agreed\nat once and without question to\ndo whatever is. necessary, a lot\nof us undoubtedly would have\ndied of the shock. If any scheme\npurporting to be progressive en\ncountered no opposition at all in\nNorth Carolina, the Daily News\nfor one, would instantly become\nsuspicious of that scheme. We\nwould fitrure that there was a\ncr-tch in it somewhere. To that\ncxtrrntthe announcement that\nuil opposition to the edu-ct.:r.-l\npro grata will be forth-\nf V v hr-tKiir.-itlii grounds\nis the,opposition to be bas2B tms.\ntime? It is-absolutely imbeojle\nto claim' that Hie '.-state cannot\nafford the expenditure. If we can\nspend $20,000,000 every year for\ngasoline and garage bills; then to\nclaim that we cannot afford $3,\n000,000 a year for six years only\nfor education is rather too\nabsurd.\nNor is there justification on the\nusual grounds of politics. The\nfiscal policy of the last legislature,\nviewed asa-whole, was distinctly\nprogressive. The opposition party\nnot only admitted that it was\nprogressive, but concentrated its\nattack on that policy, alleging\nthat it was too progressive. This\nmade the issue clear-cut the\npeople were asked, on the one\nhand to supports forward-looking\nfinancial program, and on the\nother to render a verdict that the\nmajority had been ever-zealous.\nIhe result was the most tremen\ndously emphatic vote of confi\ndence that the Democratic party\nhas ever received in this state.\nTo add to the emphasis, this vote i\nwai received in the midst of a!\nRepublican landslide. j\nHow on earth would it have\nbeen possible for the people of\nNorth Carolina to indicate more\nclearly that they believe in going\nahead? When the most con\nspicuously progressive legislature\nin years has its record endorsed\nby the biggest majority ever\nknown, how can anyone miscon\nstrue the sentiment of the state.\nSince retrogressive sentiment\ncannot claim that the state is\nfinancially disabled, nor that it\nis opposed to progress, we are\ncurious to know what will be the\nexcuse it will offer for its fight\nBusiness depression, perhaps.\nIt is a very convenient bugaboo,\nthis business depression. It is\njust formidable enough to furnish\nus with an excuse for not doing\nanything we don't want to do,\nand not substantial enough to\nprevent us from doing anything\nwe really .want to do. It is far\nand away the handiest little\nbusiness depression we have ever\nhad around the house.\nBut let U3 assume, for purposes\nof argument, that the business\ndepression i3 quite as bad as the\nopponents of progress are likel\nto claim. Let us do more let\nus assume that it is worse than\nanybody has' ever claimed. Let\nus go even one Btep further let\nus suppose that it is the worst\npanic that ever struck the coun\ntry, greatly worse than the\nRoosevelt panic, worse than the\nCleveland panic, worse than the\npanic of '73. Let us suppose\nthat it is a worse pwric than the\ncountry ever will see. After\n1873 business conditions might\nhave been described as rotten for\nabout two years, we believe,\nLet us imagine that we are going\nto have a panic twice that bad\nand then add half as much\nagain for good measure-let us\nsuppose that business win be\nbad for the next five years\nwhat then? Is North Carolina\njustified in cutting down her\neducational program on that\naccount?\nFar from it In broadening\nand strengthening the founda\ntions of her educational system\nNorth Carolina is preparing, not\nor the next five, years, but for\nthe next 20, or 30, or 40 years\nfor ps long ,as the pre\nsent generation of young\nmen and women shall live,\nTo allow such a work to\nbe interrupted, or, rather, to be\nprevented, by a temporary, busi\nness depression is nothing short\nof insensate folly.\nihe next session or the gen\neral assembly has a clear and\nunmistakable mandate from the\npeople of North Carolina to go\nforward, it caft ignore that man\ndate if it chooses; but only at\nthe price of failure in its mani\nfast duty, of betrayal of the\nhopes and aspirations of its\ncommonwealth and, what is\nworse, of the commonwealth to\nbe.-Greensboro Daily News.\nTo Our Customers and\nFriends We Extend\nOur Best Wishes\nMay you have \"The Best the world\ncan give'\nHealth to enjoy it\nWealth to buy it\nHappiness to make it worth while\nHancock\nFAMILY\nI 7\nfyg$lHFTFITTERSfl\nI ROANOKE RAPIDS, N.C.\nA. L CLARKr\nLIFE A&DTFlRtT\nINSURANCE\nLoans Negotiated on Real\nEstate\nCSS is a prescription for Colds,\nFever and' LaGrippe. It's the\nmost speedy remedy we koowadV\nE L.TRAV13, SR.\nE. L. 'TRAVIS, JR\nTRAVIS TRAVIS\nAttorneys at Law\nHALIFAX, N. C.\nPractice in the State and Federal Courts\nAllen C Zollicofter\nAttorney at Law\nRosemary, N.C\nOffk Over Old Postoffice Building\nDr. Win. A. Carter\nVeterinary Surgeon\nWELDON.N.C.\nLocal and Long Distance Pbone\n666\nwill break a Cold Fever aodGrippe\nquicker than anything we know\npreventing pnenmoBia.adv,\nSKIS\ni\nM\nerry Christmas\nand a\nHappy\nV\nNew Year\nPiano, Violin, and Small\nStringed Instruments\nin the most modern and progres\nsive manner\nLessons f 1.00 Each) $7 for Tana of\nEight Lessons\nMiss Sbaw Mrs. Murray\nmr4 314 Jackson St.\nT. W. HaSON r W. U LONG v\nllarjriburj. N. C. Roamtkt Rapids. N, C\nUS. A: MATTHEWS. RmboW Rapids, N. C.\nfl\nill\nllifl\nLq UX5 1 JMTThWS\n\nAttrneya at Law\nCfiiiesi Roanolc Rapids, N. C, and\nJackson. ft C\nSTATEMENT OF E. J. COLTRANE, SUPERINTENDENT\nROANOKE RAPIDS GRADED SCHOOL BV W.\nMcK. EVANS, CERTIFIED PUBLIC\nACCOUNTANT\nRichmond, Virginia,\nSeptember 10, 1920.\nTo the\nSchool Board,\nRoanoke Rapids, N. C.z\nGentlemec:\nBy your direction we have audited the accounting of Mr. L J.\nColtrane, Superintendent of Schools, Roanoke Rapids, North Carolina,\nand present herewith Schedules taken from his books and records,\nshowing the amounts of moneys coming into his hands from June 1919\nto June 30th, 1 920, and from what sources, amounting to I 5,740.07,\nwith disbursements segregated ot $1 22,738.20.\nThese disbursements are supported by approved vouchers, and\nthe accounts are very accurately kept\ni i i f s l. i i\nwe have maae tor Mr. ourane a much simpler and more\nsatisfactory system of accounting than the one he has been using, which\nwe think will save time and work, and give a more detailed exhibit of\nhis disbursements than was shown in the method he has been using.\nMr. 1 owe u Keeping an accurate accounting ot the moneys\nhandledby him. r\nHarrison Thomas\nClothiers Haberdashers Hatters\nRoanoke Rapids, N. jC.\nChristmas and the\nNew Year\nAltogether, we are of the opinion that the handling of\nfunds ate in safe hands. s h 'li k\nyour\nWe are gentlemen\nYours verv trulv.\nWm. McK. EVANS COMPANY\nBy, Wm. McK. Evans v v\nWMcKEiMC. Certified Public Accountant Va.\nROANOKE RAPIDS GRADED SCHOOLS\nROANOKE RAPIDS, N. C\nREPORT ON ACCOUNTING OF E. J. COLTRANE. SUPERINTENDENT\nFROM JULY 1ST, 191 TO JUNE SOTH, 1920..\n1919\nJuly 1. Balance on Hand\nreceipts:\n630.11\nJuly\nAug.\nOct.\nDec.\n1920\nJan.\nFeb.\nMarch\nApril\nMay\nJune\nNotes Discounted\nSale of Bonds\nSlater Fund\nCounty Appropriation\nLocal Tax\nRefund -County\nAppropriation\nTransfer from Book Fund\nCounty Appropriation\nNight School\nBank In erest\nLocal Tax\nDISBURSEMENTS BY MONTHS:\nJuly and Aug., 1919\nSeptember\nOctober\nNovember\nDecember\nJanuary 1920\nFebruary v\nMarch\nAnril V\nMay V\nJune\nJune\nBALANCE ON HAND:\nFirst National Bank, Roanoke Rapids\nRosemary Banking Trust Co., Rosemary\n90.00\n725.00\n498.68\n994.80\n34,000.00\n88,922.83\n\"60.00\n2,800.00\n2,332.35\n7.88\n16,120.00\n4,116.83\n1.2M.68\n220.25\n24.891.84 175,209.96\n175,740.07\n2.860.66\n10,11147\n8,242.47\n7,656.12\n4,249.45\n488.87\n4,146.80\nio.J08.24\ni 22.70166\n19,806.48\n17.916.96\n15,863.69 122.768.20\n28,090.53\n24.891.84 62.981.87\nGrateful for the confidence of our constantly\nwidening circle of customers, we take this\nopportunity to thank you for the business\ngiven us, which has helped to make this\nyear the largest year in our history.\nWe wish all a very merry chistmas and a\nHappy and prosperous new year. t\n4 Per Cent Interest on Savings\n176,740.07\nJUNE SOTH 1920\nDISBURSEMENTS SEGREGATED:\nGeneral Control\nInstructional Service\nOperation of Plant\nMaintenance of Plant\nFixed Charges 1\nDebt Service k\nCapital Outlay\nAuxiliary and Sundry Activities\nACCOUNTING OF K. C. TOWE FOR DISBURSEMENT OF CAPITAL\nUUTLAI XV JUL, I CM in, wmi.\nRECEIPTS:\nFrom Board or Scnool ITUiteea zi.eiz.70\nFromC. B. Butte 69.70\nFrom Hire of Mulea 227.89\nFrom E. E. Patrick 80.00\nWages Due 85.69 22.015.88\n2,277.94\n29,304.19\n8,636,78\n1,489.24\nS.9G6.26\n12,173.49\n69.648.62\n322.68 122,758.20\nDISBURSED:\nTo C. B.\nButts\nTo K. C. Towe, Salary\n.To IS. fatricx\nTo Labor Pay Roll\nTo Wages Due\nAmpant to Creditof K. C. Towe, July 80th In\nFirst National Sank, Roanoke Kepids\n69.70\n612.60\n80.00\n19.H.3.44\n6.S8\n20,18S.02\n1,827.98\n1,827.88\nThe First National Bank\nof Roanoke Rapids\nMember of ihe Federal Reserve System\nGAWYCH,Piest\nF. PATTERSON, V-Pret,\nJ. T. STA1NBACK, Cashier\nT. W. M. LONG, V-Prest